<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO COOK, PTSD, MISC.</font><br>
<tt>Sun Sep 21 22:00:14 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook, I have said it once, I have said it a 100 times. I never, NEVER, called viet nam vets &quot;murders&quot;. Why do you insist that I did?  I never believed they were, nor baby killers either.  I ain't a commie either, but you keep saying I am. Lets go back to our own sides of the lake, and fish, and ignore each other, cause I am getting pissed off by you putting words in my mouth that ain't true.<br><br>
The comment above about flying of Haphong<br>
Harbor and seeing Canadian ships tied up along Russian supply ships would have blown my mind had I been a pilot, and I probably would have wanted to, if not actually, launched a few at them. How F***in insane the &quot;rules&quot; must have been for you guys there.<br><br>
You know, as confusing as the Viet Nam War was, so too is it confusing for me and my reactions, some 30 years later. Perhaps that is seen as avoidance by some of you, or flip-flop by others. I can't help that. I just try and be honest with my reactions to your posts.  I am human, not some super shrink with no feelings or compassion.  Actually, I think the &quot;war&quot; in Nam should have been either faught to win within one year with all the USA had, or not faught at all.<br>
Instead, we got a long nightmare with the most wierd rules that every were written on how to kill your enemies.<br><br>
I said a long time ago, that I was a Conscientious Objector based on &quot;political beliefs&quot;. That is how my paperwork from the draft board reads. I do not think all war is evil, just the Viet Nam war was.  That is the line in the sand I drew, faught for, and finally won. And yes, I am proud of it, and Yes, I may be the first, (and only) C.O. to ever have gotten one like this, but I did.  Perhaps having seen the immediate aftermath of one war (June-July, 1967, Israel) gave me more credibility with the Selective Service System than some starry-eyed idealist college student, but I did have a better gut understanding of what war and death were all about.  Having stood in the Mitla Pass and looking at melted Egyptian tanks 4 and 5 deep, burned like crisp critters by the Israel Air Force, or a desert (Negev) covered with shoes (Egyptians ditched their shoes - they were used to walking across deserts without them), or body parts, whatever, made my position a bit stronger with the draft board.<br><br>
It also gave me a deeper understand of the fighting soldier, be it Israeli or American.  I never put down either.<br><br>
So Cook, stay on your side of the lake, I will stay on mind. Just don't put words in my mouth. Put your hook in your fish bait, not in me.  <br><br>
Who knows, maybe I have a trace of PTSD too. God knows, or my shrink, that some of my dreams are pretty wierd too.<br><br>
doc spatz<br><br>

